To this there must be a maximum limit; it is that of the creature's ability to act with such assistance (p, 145, l. 13 to p. 146, l. 12).

Can God create worlds indefinitely? If He could, then we are com- pelled to posit an infinite and absurd vacuum beyond our world. These worlds, however multiplied we may conceive them to be, would form a body infinitely small in comparison with the enormous vacuum 5111101111- ding it. We should then find one infinite magnitude to be greater than another: which is a flat absurdity. This difficulty is absolutely unanswer- able. An endless vacuum entails quite as many absurdities as the hypo- thesis ofa body infinitely great, Yet God, though thus seemingly limited in power, remains Almighty, for His power is limited only by Himself. He eternally produces an infinitely perfect act (the Word); and above all, creation implies omnipotence.
